{
  "answer": "The theological study of Allah's nature is anchored by foundational narrations in Sahih al-Bukhari (2736) and Sahih Muslim (2677) [1]. A primary narration from Sahih al-Bukhari establishes that Allah has ninety-nine names, and anyone who knows them will enter Paradise [2]. While a specifically enumerated list of these names is widely accepted from the compilation of Tirmidhi, every single name is individually attested to in the Quran or an authenticated hadith [1].\n\nSpecific authentic narrations highlight essential divine attributes that shape classical theology:\n\n*   **Infinite Mercy:** Sahih al-Bukhari records that upon completing creation, Allah wrote in His Book located with Him on His Throne, \"My Mercy overpowers My Anger\" [3].\n*   **Absolute Uniqueness:** The Prophet affirmed Allah's exclusivity after his compulsory prayers, stating that Allah has no partner in Lordship, worship, or in His Names and Qualities [4]. \n*   **Freedom from Human Limitations:** Authentic narrations strictly refute ascribing offspring to Allah or denying His power to recreate human beings, identifying such claims as a direct slight against the Creator [3, 5].\n\nThese narrations support the core theological framework that believers must accept God's attributes\u2014such as His mercy, hearing, sight, and anger\u2014exactly as He has described them [6]. This requires affirming His qualities without applying allegorical meanings, comparing them to human traits, or questioning how they exist, firmly anchored by the principle that \"There is nothing like unto Him\" [6].",
  "conversation_id": "b75c54d4-0ca8-4686-8f68-eef116d359e6",
